description.text: There are a few ear bud holder designs out there. This one is closely based on Brett Beauregard's business card ear bud holder http://brettbeauregard.com/blog/2011/06/laser-cut-business-cards/. It is designed in Open Office, and will be the basis for a student project at http://pemtech.pbworks.com/ It is expected that students will make revisions to their original design, probably at least 5, before they get the design just right. Here are the photos of the models I made to get the design to work properly: http://www.flickr.com/photos/connors934/sets/72157627576859948/ Once they get the physical design layout right, they will be able to raster a picture or their name onto the holder.

You can open up the zip file to see all the revisions. The jpg's can be used to extract a contour, and the .cst's are used with Roland Cut Studio to cut on the laser. 
In our lab, we usually use Cut Studio to drive the laser and the vinyl cutter. 
The highest version number is the most complete and accurate design.

description.text:
After searching for good 12864 case, i found some cases, but no one is perfect enough for my new Smartrap Core case. I decided to design a new one for my 12864 display. I have first before http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:855134, but it has too much holes for screws (front and back) so it's not good design. Mine is designed for RRD 12864 display. I bought it from Miniinthebox site as whole package with Arduino controller and all parts for Smartrap Core case planned build. You see in first picture the front example where i can place the 12864 case. The printer design itself has 30x30x30 printsize. The case is screwed in 12mm MDF wood at both sides. You see at back 4 sides where you can screw it in MDF panels.
(The real printer is still in progress - so real photos will added later) The case is simplified so you can just insert the 12864 RRD panel inside the front piece. The back piece will keep the display tight on the place.
Don't forget cut the selection knob a bit, to make sure it will fit in the hole at the front.
A small piece "stop" knob must inserted first before you put the 12864 panel inside.
You need 4x 3x20mm screws to fix the backplate. Not sure other 12864 panels will fit, because exactly measured thickness inside case. But RRD version should fit in most cases.
Compared to some 12864 cases, mine keep the display part inside, it will not stick out! The Smartrap Core design is here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:651117 Watch the photos so you can understand how you can make one yourself.

title: Working Steam Engine with Throttle and Reverse

description.text: I decided to take on the challenge of a reversing throttle lever as I thought it would be more fun than running over to the air compressor or moving tubes. Works well see videos! If you make it post up a pic! See the instructional video and operational video. Update (11/9/15): If you want to use this engine to drive accessories print the power take off pulley and longer crankshaft. Mount the pulley so that its grove is further from the crankshaft so your rubberband clears the pennies on the flywheel. You will need one of each part. Update: 11/9/2015 SEE THE NEW VIDEO! I have added longer crankshafts and power takeoff pulleys as well as heavier grooved flywheels to be able to drive other accessories or have the engines driven as pumps. The new flywheel fits on the crank without as much slop. With the heavier flywheels the engines will run as slow as 180 rpm on 20 PSI. The video show this engine driving (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1107379) as a water pump!

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

I used 0.2mm for everything

Infill:

I used 35% Triangles for everything

Notes: Use lots of shells and top and bottom layers for air handling parts or they will leak through their skin. I used 8 top and bottom layers and 4 shells. I used PLA at 205C, I normally use 200C but wanted the extra heat to help seal the surfaces from air leaks. I may step it up to 210C on the next one and just kick up the cooling fans.

Important: I took the spring off the throttle pivot screw and used a shorter screw to cinch it down. This has improved air leaks vastly! Should be able to use 3mm screws for everything. I use random screws I find around the shop.

description.text:
UPDATE 2015/11/17: There is a new version with interesting features: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1138434 Double Decker 175 is a mini 180 class FPV racing quad which is easy to print & build and very funny to fly due to its size and agileness. It is designed to be one of the smallest frames that accommodate 4" propellers and standard size components like 1806 motors, CC3D atom flight controller board and full size FPV camera. It's speciality is that it has two decks - in front it's tall enough to cover 32x32 mm FPV camera like Sony PZ0420. Rear part is as flat as possible so that the battery is close to the center of gravity for better flight performance. Rear part includes CC3D atom flight controller (without plastic cover) that is partly embedded to bottom plate. Behind FC is a place for VTX, ideally some flat one like TS5823. In my build there was enough space for placing X4RSB receiver on the top of FC and VTX. The frame is also designed to protect VTX antenna and motors. FPV camera plate has fixed angle of 20 degrees. Of course, this can be finely tuned by placing spacers between the camera and plate. The frame also features lightweight sidewalls to protect all the cables etc. When printed in ABS with 100% infill it's also very rigid and will survive many crashes. Total frame weight is about 70 grams (ABS, 100% infill, M2.5 self-tapping screws), AUW with FPV gear and 3s lipo 1000 mAh is about 330 grams. My recommended setup:

comments.text:
From what i have seen and read it is possible to get away without a PDB in most copters. All you have to do is to make a harness, like they have in a vehicle from silicone wire, after which you can solder plugs for the ESCs to plug in, to make it easier to service the copter, or otherwise solder the power-leads for the motors directly to the wire harness.
The other option would be to get the board that is used to make PCBs, use the one that has to have the circuits etched, with solid copper on one or both sides of the fibreglass, and then scribe lines, breaking the copper into tracks the size that you want them to use for the PDB. On the corners or somewhere on the sides of such a PDB i would then make provision for holes to mount the board to the frame of the copter.

description.text:
This is a slight rework of the same named item by qubit01. The differences are:
  • I made the wall thickness of the filament holder portion automatically calculated
  • Re-formatted the file to match my style preference.
  • While I was at it, I fixed the subtracted shapes by making them bigger by 1mm, and moving down by 0.5mm so they stuck out by 0.5mm on both sides. Because there was zero overlap between the primary and subtracted shapes, this causes a “skin” of thickness 0 which is usually considered a bad thing in modeling, and is visible on screen when compiling (F5) and can also result in artifacts in the resulting mesh under some circumstances.
    • The STL files I generated have the holes for the filament set to the exact size. If it's too tight, I just ream the holes out with the appropriately sized drill bits (e.g., 1/16 or 5/64 for 1.75mm).

Very fast filament changes, direct injection of filament (no gap to bind). Very reliable (200+ hours logged printing with 6kg of filament and a great performer easily hitting 100MM/s perimeter speeds with no problem, adaptable to other printers with minor mounting changes if desired.

Derived from MK2+ and MK4 (I was working to remove the mounting plate as Lawsy released his MK4, his was great so I moved from there); a few other's ideas or work that have been integrated Lawsy, Nophead, Tek, and more. (will edit to add where got the fan mount parts from) DI and Fan mounts are original work. lol.

Same instructions from MK4 or before, but adding a spring for the idler arm and you need to reverse "E" direction  in the firmware setting from false to true. so you won't be extruding in reverse or reflect with a CAD program to use with default settings.

If you want to etch the PCB yourself, you will need a blank 160mm x 100mm copper board and your preferred chemicals. Real-time model:

This is a parametric model for printing out glue-down mounting points for PCB boards. The trick was trying to make a part with a flat base but with a clip that would not easily break due to the direction of the layers. This solution is to print the base part and the standoff/clip part as two parts, which then press-fit together (or glue, depending on how tight your dimensions are).
This clip is designed for making simple glue-down PCB mounting clips, but the openscan code could also be extrapolated to make other types of mountings.
Recommend ABS (or nylon, I suppose), but PLA would probably work as well. For project boxes made from ABS or PVC, PVC glue could be used to fasten them down. For metal or painted surfaces, try double-sided tape or contact cement. Trim, assemble and fasten the clips to the PCB first, then glue down, to insure accurate placement.
Actually, a good mod of this would be to find pre-cut double-sided tape and size the base to match.

title: Spool Rollers for Folger Tech i3 2020

description.text: If you have a Folger Tech i3 2020, you may notice that the rolling friction on the spool is sometimes a bit too high. This can cause the extruder wheel/gear to slip a bit and gapping may occur if the filament tension is too high. Generally the existing design from Folger works well, but if you want to push print speed to the limit, you need to ensure the very lowest friction rolling for the spool and the lowest tension for the filament going into the extruder. Here is a part which you can print two of and be done with this simple upgrade, Requires one 623ZZ bearing for each roller. Often there are two extras that will come with the kit. Print two identical parts as you'll need two of them. Also, this is a universal roller setup that will work with a number of different spool types/widths. No matter the width of your spool, you can quickly move the outer of the two rollers to fit. Check out all my Folger Tech i3 2020 fixes and enhancements at http://www.thingiverse.com/pjvpjv/collections/folger-i3-2020-improvements

This is The Little Giant. This is a small safety whistle that is small enough to carry anywhere. I have included two whistles the smallest one hits about 98 decibels; the larger one get about 102 decibels.
Created these for the #MakeItLoud challenge.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

25%

Notes: Very simple design for easy printing. Be sure to print on its side so that you get a clean/sharp angle for the opening. I used ABS plastic but should not be a problem with any filament.

Had no idea how a whistle worked. When I started this project I had no idea how a whistle even worked and oddly enough a google search didn't help much. All I could find was air turbulence caused from the air crossing each other causes it to whistle; other than that nothing. So to figure this out I preformed a Design of Experiments to determine the best configuration. (Actually, It took several attempts to even get the thing to whistle at all but once I did I tried different configurations.) It turns out there is formula (per say) for a whistle. The mouth piece opening needs to be 1/2 the thickness of the overall cavity. The cavity can be as big or small (long and deep) as you like this will only affect he pitch of the whistle. As a side note anything much smaller than what I have goes out of the range of human hearing; but will drive a dog crazy. The perfect position of the angled exit hole is immediately after the end of the mouth piece. The angle exit hole has an optimal angle of 45 degrees.

description.text:
I've created those column reinforcement squads for reduce vibration on top. For 15x15 openbeam BOM: 9x M3 Screw 0.8mm length
9x M3 Nut
9x Grover washer (1mm max) The nut on the column is reworked like a T-nut (thin side, but it works) for column open beam). MOUNTING: Insert the Internal screw (with grover washer) in the hole +nut other side;
Place the external nut in right position in the open beam;
Turn the squad perpendicular to rail (column side out), insert the internal nut in the rail first, then adjust position to fit the external nut. Insert its relative screw (remember the washer);
Insert the column screw + reworked nut in squad and insert it in open beam;
Repeat this operation for all six squads, then tighten (not to death, t-nut aboveall) Fututre improvement: Connect the two column's squads for reduce printer axial torque.

title: Improved y-axis carriage attachment for prusa i3

description.text:
Too much slack due to high tolerance in smooth rods and linear bearings led my Prusa i3 to noise at any speed and to the build up of ressonance in the y-axis belt even at moderate 40mm/s printing or moving speeds. This ressonance eventually led to the belt slipping off from its pulley.
The actual rods provided by Replikeo in my kit was far from smooth and buying low tolerance rods and bearings was too expensive. I even bought some cheap high tolerance bearings in the hope that the original were simply defective but got the same results.
I finally decided that to preload the high tolerance bearings was the best solution, given that I had extra bearings now. I have designed these fittings in order to achieve this goal. It works by using three lm08uu running on each smooth rod, the central one being vertically offset by .5mm from the others.
The part worked really wel and now my printer speed is being limited by extrusion capacity only at above 65mm/s (if you can go faster, please, give me hints on what could I do to improve printing speeds), and I have yet to find the moving speed upper bound. It is true that I had once reduced my acceleration settings when trying to solve the "y-axis missed steps at moderate speeds" issue. I intend to revert those settings in the firmware and perform more testing.

Doesn't Matter

Doesn't Matter

0.25

above 26% should work

Notes: The parts were designed to be printed with the flat part touching the buildplate. Rotate it in your slicer in order to make sure you are printing them in this position.

You will need: 6 m3 nuts and screws
6 lm08uu bearings (you already have three of those in the original setting) Print the parts, fit the nuts (use the screws in order to help pushing them into place), fit the bearings and then fit both parts to the bed carriage. Finally, assemble the y-axis on the smooth rods. The only gotcha is in the latter part where the part labeled "left.stl" (but it is actually side- independent) has no room to long screws and you should try buying shorter than those I'ce got. Sorry, you will have to measure yourself but I guess around 12mm should be good enough. I tagged this as a work in progress because I intend to design grooves in the model in order to solve this issue.

description.text:
I use E3D Lite6s on my Migbots, but they're cobbled and mounted together with the existing parts, they work, but I wanted something that would be an all in one solution to mount the existing Direct Drive setup I have into. So, this is what I came up with. I use the existing extruder with the guide at the bottom cut off, so the PTFE tube can run directly to just under the gears. This is designed to mount on to the existing X axis carriage and be a direct replacement for the standard MK8 setup. If you're looking for a Bowden setup, check my other mount - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1790092 Update 21/01/2016
The Large Plate holder and Sensor mount have been updated to add strength, I got fed up of breaking plates and sensor mounts when configuring my 3rd Migbot. Update 08/06/2016
SCAD for the Top version uploaded - Disclaimer: this was designed for my use only, so the formatting and flow of the file is, er, a mess. Update 10/02/2016
It's come to my attention that it's not possible to use the mount with a Migbot with no auto level capability, so, I've moved the mount to the top and added strength to it. This should allow for use with a Migbot with no-auto level sensor and the use of the standard short sensor. This has not been tested as yet, but should work. The v2 Large plate clamp will work with this mount. Update 01/03/2016
Having just put the top mount on one of my Migbots, it seems the stock sensor mount is too low and the sensor crashes into the bed when trying to get the Z offset. I've modified the stock mount to allow more movement so the offset can be set correctly.

description.text: This is a remix of Steve Medwin's awesome Customizable Straight Beam for LEGO Technic. I added the ability to make it half-height or to have "plus"-shaped holes and cleaned up the code a bit. With these modifications you can make pieces that fit on the plus-shaped axles. To specify the number and shape of the holes in Customizer, use a string with +'s and o's. For example, the string "+ooo+" for a block with five holes: pluses at the ends and three round holes in the middle. I originally made the half-height +o+ version of this as this thing, before finding the customizable one and re-writing it around that design. As an additional feature, use a capital O for a sideways hole and a capital P for a sideways plus-shaped hole, although they probably won't print as well on most home printers. If you make a customized one of these in Customizer, please name it descriptively. Edit v3: You can use an "x" for a blank segment with no hole. title: Clicgear golf cart brake gear v2.0

description.text:
Update 4/16/2016:
When I first uploaded this thing last fall, it was at the end of golf season here in the Pacific Northwest.  I didn't get to give it much of a test.  Now that I have started golfing again this season, I realize that the original design (modeled after the factory gear) is just too weak.  I have manged to break at least 3 of them so far.  
I have redesigned the gear to have much thicker 'cogs'.  The brake still works about the same as with the factory gear.  It is only slightly harder to get the pin to drop into the space between the cogs.  So far, with about 4 rounds of golf on the prototype, it is holding up very well.  I have uploaded it as v2.0.  Print it in ABS at .2mm and 100% infill.  Skip the acetone, it doesn't help.
Original description:
Broke the brake gear on my Clicgear model 3.5+ golf cart.  Even though I could get one from Clicgear for about $5.00, I wanted to see if I could make one instead.  This one fits perfectly, but don't know if it is strong enough to hold up in use.  I printed it in ABS at .15 mm and 100% infill.  Then I dunked it into acetone for a couple of seconds.  From what I've read, that should make it as strong as possible.  
The one that Clicgear sells fits models 2.0, 3.0, and 3.5+ carts, so this one should, too.
I included a picture of the broken one for reference.
